â˜ï¸â˜ï¸â˜ï¸Minisink Valley School community:

Minisink Valley will not be running camps this summer season.

Because of the many state and local mandates and restrictions in place due to the COVID-19 outbreak, we find ourselves in the position of not being able run the many camps we know our families have enjoyed in prior years, despite the lower Hudson Valley region now in a cautious reopening period.

In addition, there will be construction taking place on the main campus as part of our Capital Project work, which would create further challenges.

We plan to resume offering camps in Summer 2021, and look forward to that happening with great optimism. We appreciate your continued understanding and support. Thank you!

ğŸ’šğŸ’š THANK YOU! Minisink Valley School District residents approved the proposed 2020-21 $99,996,558 school budget in a 3,060 to 2,305 absentee ballot vote.

The results showed 57 percent of voters approved the proposed budget.

The approved budget maintains all current student programs and services.

Additionally, Shawn Cahill, James Emery Jr. were re-elected and Patricia M. Reynolds was elected to Board of Education for a three-year term beginning July 1, 2020 through June 30, 2023. The results are:

Shawn Cahill: 2,970 votes
James Emery, Jr.: 3,082 votes
John Odland: 2,842 votes
Patricia M. Reynolds: 2,847 votes

Read more at: www.minisink.com

ğŸ’šğŸ’šğŸ’šWARRIOR Families: Today's the day!

Nelson Mandela once said: "It always seems impossible until it's done." IT'S DONE! WE DID IT!

Through all these 90 days/three months of our extended school closure, our students and parents showed how WARRIOR STRONG they are by working with our amazing teachers using technology and....being far apart. We are so proud of and grateful to everyone for all their hard work....and their academic achievements!!

You've shared hundreds and hundreds of photos with us over the last three months of your WARRIORS at WORK!

Now....here's our last batch of WARRIORS at WORK. Thank you for sharing your family's ongoing belief in the power of education through your photographic images of them working on math, physical education, ELA, science, art, social studies, music, foreign language, FACS, technology, reading or just having fun! WE LOVED sharing them, and we believe they put smiles on the faces of many people! Thank you so much!

TODAYâ€™S FEEL GOOD MOMENT!

ğŸ˜˜ğŸ’šğŸ˜˜ğŸ’š Kudos to Feeding Minisink â€œfoundersâ€ 11th-grader Ryan Nanartowicz, 10th-grader Emily Nanartowicz and eighth-grader Eileen Nanartowicz! "Feeding Minisink," their newly formed grassroots organization, is intended to help people in need since the COVID-19 outbreak happened. We LOVE seeing our students doing such wonderful things like this in our school community!

The trio recently held a food drive and used all those donations to help Kitty Uhrig and the Minisink Cares Backpack Program, in addition to a local animal shelter. Take a look at all the donations! Thank you to everyone who contributed to this effort!

To learn more, or to help the trio with their June 27 food drive at Holy Cross Church, email to: FeedingMinisink@gmail.com

Minisink Valley school community:

Your vote matters! Please vote!

The district's website, www.minisink.com, provides tremendous detail about the budget via a link on the top of the home page in the yellow alert tab called "Detailed information on the proposed 2020-21 school budget."

ALSO INCLUDED in that link are Q&As we've been asked about.....please take a look at those.

Proposed budget: $99,996,558
Proposed tax levy: 4.81%
Net tax levy: 3.94%
100% tax cap compliant
No bus proposition this year
This proposed budget will preserve all current academic, co-curricular and athletic programs and opportunities.

Thank you for your attention to this important information.

post_text:
MORE BEAUTIFUL MUSIC! MEET THE MVHS Virtual Choir!
Listen to this beautiful rendition of our National Anthem! Students rehearsed with their practice tracks at home, recorded their video performance, and then uploaded their performance to the Google classroom.

Choir Director Danielle Cornacchio then split the videos into separate audio and video tracks to bring both together for this beautiful performance.

Although the choirs were unable to be together in the classroom, they found a way to come together to create beautiful music and decided that they'd like their first virtual performance to be in honor of those who have given their lives protecting our freedoms.

Featured in this performance are students from Mixed Choir, Women's Choir and Chamber Choir!

As a reminder, in a May 1 executive order, Gov. Cuomo announced this yearâ€™s school budget vote and board of education election will take place on June 9, exclusively by absentee ballot due to the COVID-19 public health crisis.
Qualified voters are defined as U.S citizens, at least 18-years-old by June 9 and they must be a district resident for at least 30 days prior to the vote.

Because of the COVID-19 Pandemic, there is no personal voter registration held at school district offices prior to the June 9 vote.

To find out if you are registered to vote, use this link:
https://vip.ntsteamed.com/Search/VoterSearch

If you are not registered, you can register with the County Board of Elections by mail or remotely through the New York State Department of Motor Vehicles website at: https://dmv.ny.gov/more-info/electronic-voter-registration-application

If individuals are currently registered to vote with the district, they will automatically receive an absentee ballot and do not need to register.

A STORY FOR ALL!

Middle school librarian Maggie Spicehandler, with help from her husband Matt, connects with her library studentsâ€¦..actually, every studentâ€¦ through her presentation of the West Africian folktale, â€œAbiyoyo.â€

In this book based on a South African lullaby and folktale, a fearsome giant, Abiyoyo, suddenly appears in a small South African town, causing the people to run for their lives. Nothing can stop the giant except for the sound of a little boy's ukulele â€” a sound that enchants the giant, but a sound that up until now none of the boy's fellow townspeople could stand to hear.

The boy's father also has a special gift: He can wave a magic wand and make things disappear, a talent the townspeople have found equally annoying. But now, the previously banished boy and his father are suddenly heroes, as they work together to get rid of Abiyoyo for good.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m-yy8uFRuRA&feature=youtu.be

Gather your children and watch!

ğŸ¤“ğŸ¤“ğŸ¤“ A PENNY SAVED IS MORE THAN JUST A PENNY EARNED!

Kim Marascoâ€™s and Jessica Venettozziâ€™s Intermediate School fourth-graders recently completed a home science experiment using pennies, a great representation of the innovative ways the Minisink Valley faculty are working remotely with students!

Students studied changes in matter and observed the chemical changes that happen to pennies using vinegar.

They also read about how the Statue of Liberty used to be like a shiny penny and why it's now a greenish color. (SPOILER ALERT: When the statue was unveiled in 1886, it was a shiny brown color, like a penny. By 1906, the color had changed to green. The reason the Statue of Liberty changed colors is that the outer surface is covered with hundreds of thin copper sheets. Copper reacts with the air to form a patina or verdigris.)

post_text:
May the music be with you!

Otisville music teachers Skyler Klein and Maria Fenfert created a bucket drumming video as a fun musical activity for Otisville Elementary students --- actually, ANYONE--- to mark May 4, the day where Star Wars fans worldwide like to pronounce: â€œMay the fourth be with you!â€

In the video, Mrs. Fenfert shows the students how to play a bucket as a drum and teaches them six simple rhythms to be played. Then, Mr. Klein performs the piece in its entirety. The rhythms are displayed through the video to guide students and reinforce their music reading. This week's theme was Star Wars, appropriately noting the significance of May 4, featuring the song, â€œCantina,â€ from â€œStar Wars Episode IV: A New Hope.â€

Watch the video, get some buckets, find something to use as sticks, and follow along!

HERE'S MORE STUDENT ARTISTIC CREATIVENESS!

Kat Hoolanâ€™s high school â€œAdvanced Darkroom Photographyâ€ and â€œStudio in Photographyâ€ students continue to be busy with their at home assignments, and weâ€™re sharing their â€œFlat Lay Photographyâ€ creativeness with you!

Flat Lay Photography is a type of still life photo shot top down (otherwise known as a birdâ€™s eye view).

Objects are arranged or organized in such a way that the viewer's eye moves around the composition, rather than settling on one focal point. A lot of flat lays center around a theme or tell a story. The objects' arrangement in the composition is important to create something aesthetically pleasing to look at. Flat lays can be found in magazines, Pinterest and other forms of advertising and blogs. Take a look!
